title: "Man arrested for bringing pistols to music festival; no injuries"
lastUpdated: 2022-08-23
---

On Aug. 19 at around 9 p.m, police arrested a man at the Bass Canyon Music Festival for possessing two loaded pistols. Around 25,000 people attended the festival. Witnesses said they observed a man inhaling gas from a balloon, loading two 9 mm pistols from his car and tucking the pistols into his waistband. The Grant County Sheriff's Office said they do not feel the suspect intended to cause a mass shooting. There were no injuries.

"The suspect, later identified as 31-year-old Jonathan R. Moody of Ephrata, approached concertgoers, asking what time the concert ended and where people would be exiting the venue," read a Facebook post from the Grant County Sheriff's Office. "Moody did not make access inside the venue. Venue security detained Moody outside of the venue gates and disarmed him of the two loaded 9mm pistols." Moody was booked into the Grant County Jail but has since been released after posting a $10,000 bail.

Initially, police believed that Moody intended to cause a mass shooting. However, in another Facebook post on Aug. 23, they said that they no longer believe this to be the case, after interviewing Moody and serving a search warrant on two of his vehicles. Their investigation is still ongoing.

"It should be noted that Jonathan [Moody] does have a valid concealed weapons permit," the arresting officer said to KIRO 7. Regardless, the Gorge Ampitheater, where the festival was held, does not allow weapons on site.

Police say that possession of weapons was only one of the reasons Moody was arrested.

"Moody’s actions of appearing to inhale an intoxicant, loading weapons in the parking lot, and his questions about where concertgoers would be exiting and at what time, furthered the suspicions of witnesses and deputies," read the first Facebook post from the sheriff's office about the incident.

Moody is next scheduled to appear in court on Sept. 8.

